How to build a Content based Image Retrieval engine

Robert Kyle

 Thu 08 January 2015
Category: Tutorial

In this tutorial I'm going to show you how you can use the image features provided by image awesome to build a content based image retrieval engine for your images. This could be useful in surfacing similar content, detecting duplicate products in your database, or finding unlicensed usage of your images.

To demonstrate this I'm going to use a corpus of images collected from flickr. I'll show you how to do it in python, but all of these tasks can be done in any language

1. The dataset

First let's download the dataset:

curl -o flickr_style.csv.gz https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BVLC/caffe/master/examples/finetune_flickr_style/flickr_style.csv.gz

2. Extract features from the images with image awesome

Visit http://imageawesome.com/upload to upload your CSV file for processing. When the processing is complete you will receive an email with a link to the HDF5 file containing your image features.

Let's download the file, and rename it flickr_20k_features.hdf5

3. Quantifying image similarity with Locality Sensitive Hashing

Now that we reduced the images to 4096 floating point values, we can use techniques like Locality Sensitive Hashing (LSH) to provide a measure of the similarity between the image features.

Locality Sensitive Hashing is a probabilistic dimensionality reduction method. Unlike most dimensionality reduction techniques, Locality Sensitive Hashing attempts to maximise rather than minimise the likelihood of collision for similar vectors. This means that images with similar features will be placed close together in the new, lower-dimensional feature-space. In this sense LSH has more in common with clustering algorithms.

We're going to use the LSHForest implementation in scikit-learn, as it is simple to use, and the fit and query time scale well as the dataset grows. LSHForest is available in version 0.16 of scikit-learn, which at the time of writing is in development. You can install the dev version of scikit-learn directly from the github repo.

pip install git+https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn.git

First let's load our image features into memory.

4. Finding similar images

Searching for similar images is fast with the LSHForest algorithm

In [33]: 
%time distances, indexes = forest.kneighbors(data['features'][:6], n_neighbors=6)

Wall time: 166 ms

Let's render the images to see how good the results are.

In [37]: 
import numpy as np
import skimage.io
from scipy.ndimage import zoom

def center_crop_image(url):
    """
    Scale and center-crop the images, so they appear as the neural network sees them
    """
    image = skimage.io.imread(url)
    
    # intepret greyscale images as RGB
    if image.ndim == 2:
        image = image[:, :, np.newaxis]
        image = np.tile(image, (1, 1, 3))
    
    # resize the image
    input_image_dimensions = np.array([227, 227])
    scale = input_image_dimensions[0].astype('float32') / np.array(image.shape)[:2]
    
    # scale up or down in size?
    if scale.min() <= input_image_dimensions.min():
        zoom_factor = scale.max()
    else:
        zoom_factor = scale.min()
    
    resized_image = zoom(image, (zoom_factor, zoom_factor, 1), order=1)
    
    # centre crop the image
    center = np.array(resized_image.shape[:2]) / 2.0
    crop = np.tile(center, (1, 2))[0] + np.concatenate([-input_image_dimensions / 2.0, input_image_dimensions / 2.0])
    center_cropped_image = resized_image[crop[0]:crop[2], crop[1]:crop[3], :]
    return center_cropped_image

def load_similar_images(indexes):
    """
    load them into memory for easier rendering
    """
    images = np.zeros(indexes.shape + (227, 227, 3), dtype='uint8')
    for i in range(indexes.shape[0]):
        for j in range(indexes.shape[1]):
            url = data['processed_urls'][indexes[i, j]]
            images[i, j] = center_crop_image(url)

    return images

images = load_similar_images(indexes)
In [36]: 
%matplotlib inline
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

def plot_similar_images(distances, images, indexes, figure_title="Similar Images"):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=6, ncols=6, figsize=(12, 12))
    fig.suptitle(figure_title, fontsize=30)
    for row in xrange(indexes.shape[0]):
        for column in xrange(indexes.shape[1]):
            axes[row, column].xaxis.set_visible(False)
            axes[row, column].yaxis.set_visible(False)
            if column == 0:
                title = "Original"
            else:
                title = "{0:.3f}".format(distances[row, column])
            axes[row, column].set_title(title)
            axes[row, column].imshow(images[row, column])

plot_similar_images(distances, images, indexes)

the results are quite impressive given how small our sample is - 20,000 images.

The benefits of using imagenet features for this similarity search, is that the performance (in terms of the distance metric) is a function of the size and breadth of the imagenet database, rather than the size of our relatively small dataset.

To demonstrate that the performance of the search is not strongly dependent on the fitting of the LSHForest, let's render some results from images that were not seen the the LSHForest algorithm.

In [38]: 
unseen_distances, unseen_indexes = forest.kneighbors(data['features'][-6:], n_neighbors=6)
unseen_images = load_similar_images(unseen_indexes)
In [41]: 
plot_similar_images(unseen_distances, unseen_images, unseen_indexes, figure_title="Similar images - Unseen")

6. Conclusion

We've shown with a very small dataset, that it is possible to use the imagenet features extracted by image awesome to build a Content Based Image Retrieval engine that works with natural images, including images that it was not trained on.
